title: For Sale:  KOREAN WAR ERA BANDOLIER'S,30-06 FOR SPRINGFIELD M1 GARAND, 4 BANDOLIERS, 230RDS TOTAL
postcontent:
4 bandoliers , with 230 rounds total 30-06

St. Louis Ordnance Plant in 1953, in lot numbers one through four . It was a contract for the U.S. Government, for ammunition for use in whatever convert operations they chose to use it in. It was not made specifically for the "Bay of Pigs" fiasco.
Similar rounds were made by Twin Cities (AN) and Lake City (CN).

These rounds are, like all ammunition, collectible, but are not rare. It is packed in a standard olive-drab 6six-pocket U.S. bandoleer, each pocket holding two, five-shot Springfield-type steel clips, with end tabs, nestled in a carboard pocket within the pocket of the bandoleer intself. Standard U.S. packaging, although the use of Springfield clips in a 1953 contract is interesting of itself, and I have no information as to why that particular arrangement was done.

The bandoleer has no markings other than a stampled representation of the cartridge's headstamp on it.

The ammunition is Ball M2 Alternate, which differs from Ball M2 in having a GMCS bullet jacket, rather than a GM jacket. Bullet weight is 150 grains.
The primer is non-corrosive.

Reference: ".30-06", by Chris Punnett, page 312. (This is one of the "must have books" for anyone interested in U.S. military ammunition). 

Art REDACTED Call or Text

title: For Sale/Trade:  Browning Hi Power - John Inglis with tangent sights
postcontent:
Up for sale or trade is a Canadian made Browning Hi Power (by John Inglis for Chinese contract). This is a World War II era gun.  If only it could talk…

Before the fall of Belgium to the Nazi’s, FN moved what they could to England for building the FN/Browning Hi Power 9mm pistol; one of the few weapons of the war that was used by both sides. Once in England, it was decided to move production to Canada to support the war effort. The Inglis Company was chosen and the rest is history.

The name Hi Power speaks for itself.  This is a bit of a Frankenstein gun, but it shoots very reliably and is very accurate.

Many Inglis Hi Powers were made for the Chinese Army and shipped from Canada. This is one of them. I call it Frankenstein because none of the numbers match which was common with Chinese guns as repairs were made to keep them in the field with other parted out guns.

The frame has a serial number of 19655 which indicates that it was a pre-war built frame.  I've been told it was 1938.  The slide is 4CH575 and the barrel is 3CH4932, which indicate both of these were built in 1945. 

The grips are authentic Inglis grips with the cooresponding proof marks on the back sides (I have pictures if needed).

A unique feature of the Chinese Hi Powers was the wooden Mauser Broom Handle-like stock they came with, hence the cut-out on the rear of the grip. The stock to this one is long gone but a replica can be made to restore it to original condition. Also unique the Chinese Hi Power is the tangent rear sight.  It was designed for use out to 500 meters with the stock.

If you have any questions or want additional photos please text me (9one8 6two5 2629) with what you’d like to see.  I will include a hard case and 50 rounds of UMC 115gr 9mm.
